data.content:
Here's the modernized version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

Key changes:
1. Remove the `[ExpectedException]` attribute
2. Wrap the throwing call in `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>(() => ...)`

This is better because it pinpoints *exactly which line* must throw. With `[ExpectedException]`, any line in the method throwing `ArgumentNullException` would pass — including the constructor — masking bugs.

If you also need to verify the exception message or properties:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
    () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```

> **Note:** `ThrowsExactly` requires an exact type match. If you need to accept derived exception types, use `ThrowsException<T>` instead.
